fields.title: Daniel Myers, mmmhhh, he's so cute
fields.content: I know it sounds wrong, but i just want to own this man...But I must explain to you how all this mistaken idea of denouncing pleasure and praising pain was born and I will give you a complete account of the system, and expound the actual teachings of the great explorer of the truth, the master-builder of human happiness. No one rejects, dislikes, or avoids pleasure itself, because it is pleasure, but because those who do not know how to pursue pleasure rationally encounter consequences that are extremely painful. Nor again is there anyone who loves or pursues or desires to obtain pain of itself, because it is pain, but because occasionally circumstances occur in which toil and pain can procure him some great pleasure. To take a trivial example, which of us ever undertakes laborious physical exercise, except to obtain some advantage from it? But who has any right to find fault with a man who chooses to enjoy a pleasure that has no annoying consequences, or one who avoids a pain that produces no resultant pleasure? fields.title: Sharkz attackz
fields.content: Shark attackz are bad. On the other hand, we denounce with righteous indignation and dislike men who are so beguiled and demoralized by the charms of pleasure of the moment, so blinded by desire, that they cannot foresee the pain and trouble that are bound to ensue; and equal blame belongs to those who fail in their duty through weakness of will, which is the same as saying through shrinking from toil and pain. These cases are perfectly simple and easy to distinguish. In a free hour, when our power of choice is untrammelled and when nothing prevents our being able to do what we like best, every pleasure is to be welcomed and every pain avoided. But in certain circumstances and owing to the claims of duty or the obligations of business it will frequently occur that pleasures have to be repudiated and annoyances accepted. The wise man therefore always holds in these matters to this principle of selection: he rejects pleasures to secure other greater pleasures, or else he endures pains to avoid worse pains.

fields.title: My Annoying Teammate, Jonathan
fields.content: Chesney here. I was coding with my bros when a strange man appeared. He looked homeless, and I could smell him through zoom. His name was Jonathan. He was really lame. My really cool, unlame friend — Daniel — looked at Jonathan and said, You are really lame. Youre in the wrong group. Kindly leave. But Jonathan did not kindly leave. He was like Can I code with yall, please? I dont have any friends. I took pity on the unfortunate-looking man and said Sure, you can code with us. This would end up being the biggest mistake of my life. While we were working on Django, hed make the same joke over and over again. Whenever the server dropped a 4hundo error, he would say, Looks like its Django Unchained. Or Quentin Tarantino couldnt write code like this. Or whos Django Reinhardt? Or hed repeat the word Django over and over and over again. Daniel, meanwhile, was being extremely passive aggressive towards me. Whenever I complained about Jonathans perverse obsession with Sex and the City, Daniel would respond, Well, we didnt have to invite him into our group. Glad we made a team decision. Cassie, meanwhile, was on chatGPT, generating cat images and obscure backgrounds for her zoom. Our team was truly falling apart.
